      "writtenOn": "2016-07-27T15:53:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It looks like the only purpose of this class is to encapsulate a global name, and provide \"convenience\" wrappers around glGenXXX() and glDeleteXXX() context-specific pointers.\n\nHowever, replacing a single 32-bit uint with a shared-pointer to a structure that contains multiple pointers seems a _little_ overkill to me.\n\nE.g. it looks like you could do the same by adding a context-specific genXXX()/delXXX() callbacks.",
      "revId": "1dbfa3de25b89664183f398d316a4f6ca2cbb6a5",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6fff696c_bf85fc6c",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/Translator/include/GLcommon/NamedObject.h",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 62,
      "author": {
        "id": 1087303
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-07-27T18:54:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The other purpose is to have the appropriate reference counter for texture object, which is frequently shared across contexts / share groups because of EglImage.\n\nThe reason I have to keep a glDeleteXXX function pointer is somehow tricky. This code is build into a static library (libGLcommon), it is linked by (at least) 3 shared libraries (EGL_translator, GLES_V2_translator, GLES_CM_translator). Each shared library has its own GLEScontext::dispatcher. EGL_translator does not even initialize its dispatcher. So if we just call the static GLEScontext::dispatcher().glDeleteXXX, we might end up calling a null function because the dispatcher is not initialized in the current shared library :(\n\nSo I have to point glDeleteXXX to the shared library that has the appropriate function...",
      "parentUuid": "af11619a_246f7298",
      "revId": "1dbfa3de25b89664183f398d316a4f6ca2cbb6a5",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
